def: The chief tower, also called the keep; a massive tower inancient castles, forming the strongest part of the fortifications.See Illust. of Castle.
The jamb or sidepiece of a doorway.
Of or pertaining to both the temple and the ear; as, thetemporo-auricular nerve.
A source, spring, or fountain.At the wellhead the purest streams arise. Spenser.Our public-school and university life is a great wellhead of new andirresponsible words. Earle.
One of several pieces fayed across the apron and lapped in theknightheads, or inside planking above the upper deck. Ham. Nav.Encyc.
The system of writing in ideographic characters; also, anythingso written.
A small collection of sheaves set up in the field; a shock; inEngland, twelve sheaves.
To encircle with a garland, or with garlands. Sir P. Sidney.
A noun that has four cases only. Andrews.
A shoot or secondary stem growing from the main stem, or from aprincipal limb or bough of a tree or other plant.
